The paper deals with the problem of modeling and recognizing faults in a real-world smart grid system, which involves the use of machine learning techniques such as dissimilarity measures learning and one-class classification. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper deals with a real-world system and involves the use of sensors and data analysis, which suggests that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves the use of decision rules and analysis of results, which suggests that it may also belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category.
